**Operating system or device - Godot version:**
Godot legacy branch compiled 19/01/2017

**Issue description:**
Using str2var and var2str functions on a dictionary containing a dictionary, I've been trying to erase keys in the child dictionary but nothing happens. I hadn't the same problem with str2bytes and bytes2str.


**Steps to reproduce:**
```gdscript
	var o = {
		"p": {
			"q": 1
		}
	}
	print("Basic use of erase:")
	print(var2str(o), " should be { \"p\":{ \"q\":1 } }") # prints { "p":{ "q":1 } }
	o.p.erase("q")
	print(var2str(o), " should be { \"p\":{  } }") # prints { "p":{  } }, like expected
	
	var o2 = {
		"p": {
			"q": 1
		}
	}
	print("Erase after use of var2str and str2var:")
	print(var2str(o2), " should be { \"p\":{ \"q\":1 } }") # prints { "p":{ "q":1 } }
	o2 = str2var(var2str(o2))
	o2.p.erase("q")
	print(var2str(o2), " should be { \"p\":{  } }") # prints { "p":{ "q":1 } }, erase function didn't work
	
	var o3 = {
		"p": {
			"q": 1
		}
	}
	print("Erase after use of var2bytes and bytes2var:")
	print(var2str(o3), " should be { \"p\":{ \"q\":1 } }") # prints { "p":{ "q":1 } }
	o3 = bytes2var(var2bytes(o3))
	o3.p.erase("q")
	print(var2str(o3), " should be { \"p\":{  } }") # prints { "p":{  } }, like expected
```


The output of this is
```
Basic use of erase:
{ "p":{ "q":1 } } should be { "p":{ "q":1 } }
{ "p":{  } } should be { "p":{  } }

Erase after use of var2str and str2var:
{ "p":{ "q":1 } } should be { "p":{ "q":1 } }
{ "p":{ "q":1 } } should be { "p":{  } }

Erase after use of var2bytes and bytes2var:
{ "p":{ "q":1 } } should be { "p":{ "q":1 } }
{ "p":{  } } should be { "p":{  } }
```

I'm not math specialist but I think Vector reflect() math is wrong'ish.

When I'v checked the Godot source, code looked like this:

Vector2 Vector2::reflect(const Vector2 &p_vec) const {
	return p_vec - *this * this->dot(p_vec) * 2.0;
}

It produced results that don't look like correct vector reflection.

Shouldn't formula be:
-(vec - vec.dot(normal) * 2 * normal)
